-- Deals of the day- Mergers and acquisitions
-- 
-- Thu Apr 17, 2014 06:21AM EDT
-- None



April 17 (Reuters) - The following bids, mergers, acquisitions and disposals were reported by 1000 GMT on Thursday:

** Standard Chartered's <STAN.L> planned sale of its Hong Kong consumer finance unit has drawn first-round bids from suitors like Carlyle Group <CG.O> and Bain Capital, lured by the unit's industry-beating returns, people familiar with the matter said. [ID:nL3N0N919L]  ** Central and eastern Europe's largest insurer PZU <PZU.WA> has bought three Baltic rivals and a stake in one Polish firm from troubled British group RSA Insurance <RSA.L> for a total of 348 million euros ($481 million), marking its largest acquisition in history, it said on Thursday. [ID:nL6N0N91M0]  ** Nationalised Austrian lender Hypo Alpe Adria [HAABI.UL] may sell its Balkans banking network this year, ahead of the mid-2015 deadline set by the European Commission in return for approving state aid for the loss-making lender, it said on Thursday. [ID:nV9N0MP00O]  ** Israeli conglomerate Delek Group <DLEKG.TA> said on Thursday its subsidiary Delek Europe Holdings signed a memorandum of understanding to sell Delek Europe BV to a foreign fund for 355 million euros ($490.1 million). [ID:nL6N0N91M6]  ** Cereal maker Post Holdings Inc <POST.N> is close to a deal to acquire eggs and dairy producer and distributor Michael Foods Group Inc for $2.5 billion, prevailing over a rival bid from Tyson Foods Inc <TSN.N>, said a person familiar with the matter. [ID:nL2N0N81QI]  ** Chemtura Corp <CHMT.N> plans to sell its agrochemicals business to Platform Specialty Products Corp <PAH.N> for about $1 billion, the Wall Street Journal reported, citing people familiar with the matter. [ID:nL3N0N90R6]  ** India's Piramal Enterprises Ltd <PIRA.NS> said it agreed to buy a 20 percent stake in unlisted Shriram Capital Ltd for 20.14 billion rupees ($334 million), increasing its foothold in the financial services sector. [ID:nL3N0N90VB]  ** Australian developer Meriton Group is considering a A$3 billion ($2.8 billion) offer from a Chinese developer for half its apartment business, according to a media report, highlighting increasing Chinese interest in Australia's housing market. [ID:nL3N0N8585]  ** Discovery Communications <DISCA.O> has dropped out of bidding to buy Britain's free-to-air Channel 5, according to two sources familiar with the matter. [ID:nL2N0N82DU] ($1 = 0.7243 Euros) ($1 = 1.0674 Australian Dollars)